This was a spread of large pieces of fresh-looking bone along with reedy phytoliths in the outdoor area with hearths under B. 65. It is a moderate size unit, which does not fit easily into our usual categories. There is a wide range of taxa: sheep/goat, cattle, red deer, equid, dog. There is a somewhat higher proportion of larger taxa than usual, and a much higher ratio of diagnostics to scrap. Meaty parts predominate, although there are some heads and feet. There are big pieces of mandibles of 3 different cattle. A couple of the sheep specimens are massive and possibly wild. There is quite a bit of perinatal sheep/goat, distributed through the body so perhaps originally a whole animal, although there is an MNI of 2. But I am sure Roddy would have noticed if it were articulated in the ground. There are also many unfused ends still with their shafts, showing little disturbance. Fragmentation is fairly low; certainly no bone grease processing, although some phalanges with fresh surfaces are fragmented. Surface condition includes many notably fresh bones, and also some that are a bit more worn and weathered. Either there are multiple origins, or a dump that then lay exposed for a while so the bones on the top deteriorated a bit. One notable specimen is a dog maxilla that has been smushed into a pancake, perhaps by heavy activity on top of it. Little or no burning. A little gnawing, and quite a few digested pieces, many still coated with coprolite material that may have come from one (very big) or more coprolites. So dogs seem to have had some access, but have certainly not worked it over much. This certainly looks like primarily, although not exclusively, post-consumption discard, but it must represent more than one meal. Perhaps the part of a big feast that came home to this household created a disposal issue that led to a special dump along with remains of other meals that had accumulated? Sample 2 >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as diagnostics and flot frags only. It is a moderate size sample that in some respects parallels the dry-sieved. There are some likely fragments of pieces recorded in the dry-sieved, and a few of the very fresh bits. While there are a couple of digested sesamoids and a calcaneus fragment, feet are still scarce. However, there is much less large mammal in the flot, which is heavily although not entirely sheep-size, and far fewer diagnostics of any kind. Except for a couple of cattle incisor fragments, the diagnostics are all sheep/goat. Fragmentation is higher in the flot sample, even allowing for the addition of little bits. Surface condition is variable, with a few very fresh, a fair number in good shape, a majority slightly worn, and a few quite worn. There is a certain amount of digestion. About 10% are burnt at all temperatures. This sample looks more like fill of multiple origins. The fresh dumping event really seems to be confined to the larger pieces.
Scanned for C14 samples 7/8/12 and the following extracted: F47, F48, F109, F116, F131, F132, F133, F134, F146, F147, F150,
